---
// Install page: spec.md "Install (/install)".
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';

const sourceDownloadUrl = 'https://github.com/ContextCake/context-cake/archive/refs/tags/console-v0.2.0.tar.gz';
---

<Base
	title="Install ContextCake"
	description="Install ContextCake from a source archive. Plain Node.js ≥ 18, no dependency install step."
>
	<main>
		<h1>Install</h1>

		<p class="lede">
			Download the source archive and unpack it. The engine runs on Node.js without an{' '}
			<code>npm install</code> step, install scripts, or runtime packages.
		</p>

		<h2>Prerequisites</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>A browser to download the source archive</li>
			<li>Node.js ≥ 18</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>1. Download the source archive</h2>
		<a class="download-link" href={sourceDownloadUrl} download>Download ContextCake (.tar.gz)</a>
		<p>
			This downloads the versioned <code>console-v0.2.0</code> source archive directly from
			ContextCake's GitHub repository.
		</p>

		<h2>2. Unpack it</h2>
		<CodeBlock
			lang="bash"
			code={`mkdir contextcake
	tar -xzf context-cake-console-v0.2.0.tar.gz -C contextcake --strip-components=1
cd contextcake`}
		/>

		<h2>3. Resolve your first concept</h2>
		<p>
			The archive includes a small three-layer example. This command resolves one concept
			and returns the selected values, their sources, and any conflicts:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			lang="bash"
			code={`node resolver.mjs --manifest apps/playground/manifest.json --concept decisions/primary-db`}
		/>
		<p>
			The JSON response identifies the layer used for each section. Other values appear in
			the <code>conflicts</code> array with their source dates.
		</p>

		<h2>4. Serve it to an agent</h2>
		<p>Start the MCP server against the same demo bundle:</p>
		<CodeBlock
			lang="bash"
			code={`node mcp-server.mjs --manifest apps/playground/manifest.json`}
		/>
		<p>Or register it with an MCP client (Claude Code shown):</p>
		<CodeBlock
			lang="bash"
			code={`claude mcp add contextcake -- node /path/to/context-cake/mcp-server.mjs --manifest /path/to/context-cake/apps/playground/manifest.json`}
		/>
		<p>
			From here, point the manifest at your own layers. See{' '}
			<a href="/docs/getting-started/first-cascade">Your first cascade</a> and{' '}
			<a href="/docs/getting-started/connect-an-agent">Connect an agent</a>.
		</p>

		<h2>Optional: explore visually</h2>
		<CodeBlock lang="bash" code={`npm run playground   # http://127.0.0.1:8790`} />
		<p>
			The playground shows the same sources, resolved values, and conflicts in a browser.
			Its libraries are included in the archive, so it does not fetch them at runtime.
		</p>

		<h2>Source checkout</h2>
		<p>
			Use a git checkout when you want to inspect history, contribute changes, or pin your
			own fork:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			lang="bash"
			code={`git clone https://github.com/ContextCake/context-cake.git
cd context-cake`}
		/>

		<h2>A note on trust</h2>
		<p>
			The manifest is a trust boundary: a layer with <code>"source": "mcp"</code> spawns
			the command it names, as your user. Only point ContextCake at manifests you wrote
			or trust. The same rule applies to any MCP client config.{' '}
			<a href="/docs/concepts/trust-boundary">Read the details</a>.
		</p>

		<h2>Why a source archive?</h2>
		<p>
			A source archive keeps the initial trust decision small. You can inspect the code you
			are about to run, and there is no registry install step or transitive runtime package
			tree. ContextCake still requires care around manifests, because an MCP source can run
			the command named in that manifest.
		</p>
	</main>
</Base>

<style>
	main {
		max-width: 46rem;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 3rem 1.5rem;
	}
	.lede {
		font-size: 1.1rem;
	}
	h2 {
		margin-top: 2.5rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
	}
	code {
		font-family: var(--cc-font-mono);
	}
	p code, li code {
		background: var(--cc-surface);
		border: 1px solid var(--cc-border);
		border-radius: 4px;
		padding: 0.1rem 0.35rem;
		font-size: 0.9em;
	}
	a {
		color: var(--cc-layer-team);
	}
	.download-link {
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: center;
		min-height: 44px;
		padding: 0.65rem 1rem;
		border: 1px solid var(--cc-cta);
		border-radius: 999px;
		background: var(--cc-cta);
		color: var(--cc-on-cta);
		font-family: var(--cc-font-heading);
		font-weight: 700;
		text-decoration: none;
	}
	.download-link:hover {
		background: var(--cc-cta-hover);
	}
</style>
